  "contents": [
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "For information about how to do Lessons 2 – 71, please read **How to Use this Book**."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "Note – to aid memorization, words and examples can be hidden by selecting \"hide all\" or by selecting individually."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "In this lesson, we will learn to ask questions with “who”, which is _sino _in Tagalog. For a complete list of Tagalog question words, see **Appendix K**. We will also use this lesson as our introduction to Tagalog sentences and the _ang _form. If you are not familiar with _ang_ form noun markers, or need a refresher, please go to **Appendix A** and memorize them before attempting this lesson."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "Here is a little review of English grammar. The **subject** of a sentence is the person/thing that is doing or being something. The **predicate** is the rest of the sentence. For more English grammar definitions, please see **Appendix M**."
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "markdown": "**Sino** + subject? (Tag.) = Who is the subject? (Eng.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "h3",
      "markdown": "**Note: Subject takes _ang_ form.**"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "In this book, the equation shown in big text above is called a Structure Equation. Terms like “Structure Equation” and abbreviations that are unique to this book can be found in **Appendix N**."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Sino ang guro?",
        "english": "Who is the teacher?",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "a480b5ef-8434-40fa-896e-6b46c1f84aac"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Sino ang mga lalaki?",
        "english": "Who are the men?",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "c08f985c-6a71-46aa-9508-f1487d11d70a"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Sino ang pangulo?",
        "english": "Who is the president?",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "8a7127ad-37ab-44f0-8bbe-7ca6961f8541"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "To answer these questions, you can use the following:"
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "markdown": "**Predicate** + subject. (Tag.) = Subject is the predicate. (Eng.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "h3",
      "markdown": "**Note: Subject and predicate take _ang_ form**."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Si Mrs. Castillo ang guro.",
        "english": "The teacher is Mrs. Castillo.",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "f4d74eda-ec87-4042-b90d-d1dcb6eb8a34"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Sina Joshua at Joaquin ang mga lalaki.",
        "english": "The men are Joshua and Joaquin.",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "974a56ff-32f2-4e1a-a3d8-a4fe348c066c"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Si Sir Bautista ang pangulo.",
        "english": "The president is Mr. Bautista.",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "707112da-69bf-4a49-9b09-284d3685e5cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "Remember that direct family member nouns, like _nanay_, are usually marked by the same noun markers that mark names."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Si nanay ang guro.",
        "english": "The teacher is mother.",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "93ecb9ea-3f20-41d9-b6da-047733a840ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "h3",
      "markdown": "<u>Extra: Sino-sino</u>"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "There is a special word for “who” that is used with plurals. It is _sino-sino_, or _sinu-sino_. Here is an example:"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "item": {
        "tagalog": "Sino-sino ang mga lalaki?",
        "english": "Who are the men?",
        "required": true,
        "audioPath": "cc9ed333-f267-40ec-a5ca-d44c640ce279"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "It is good to be able to recognize this, but it is not used very often in colloquial speech. You are better off using _sino_, so we will not mention _sino-sino_ again."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "markdown": "This is not all - we will go deeper into _sino_ in later lessons."
    }
  ],
